{"Body": "<!-- p.p1 {margin: 0.0px 0.0px 0.0px 0.0px; text-align: right; font: 13.0px 'Helvetica Neue'} p.p2 {margin: 0.0px 0.0px 0.0px 0.0px; text-align: justify; text-indent: 10.0px; font: 9.0px 'Whitney HTF'} span.s1 {letter-spacing: -0.1px} -->Sebastien LeCocq\n\nSS History &amp; Philosophy\n\n<strong>President</strong>\n\nSebastien Lecocq is an outspoken Englishman with an eye on pipping his fellow Englishman, Bartlett, to the Presidential post.\n\nAn altogether different candidate to Bartlett&rsquo;s CV-filled manifesto, Lecocq says that what he lacks in extra-curricular experience, he makes up for in dedication and ideas. The twenty-two year old has dedicated himself to getting &ldquo;the best possible grade&rdquo; in his degree and immersing himself in the Irish culture.\n\nA class rep this year, the History and Philosophy student has attended SU Council regularly to ask &ldquo;pertinent questions&rdquo;. LeCocq is of the opinion that SU is far too centred on the fees issue. While he acknowledges the importance of this issue to Trinity students, he feels that the SU is out of touch with the student body.\n\n&ldquo;For instance, though we should campaign against fees and lobby TD&rsquo;s, we should definitely not be unofficially supporting particular parties just because they support us on one issue,&rdquo; said Lecocq. &ldquo;The SU should not be affiliated with particular parties and &lsquo;suggesting&rsquo; to vote certain ways, is not part of what the SU was set up to do. After all, though a party may support us on fees does not mean that their policies, as a whole over the long-term, will be in the benefit of future students and the country as a whole.&rdquo;\n\nLecocq has a novel approach to combating the cuts in the student grant. &ldquo;I wish to introduce a grant from the SU, to these poorer students. We would not ask for this money back. I would fund this by cutting back on the costs of class rep training, and other areas of SU expenditure.&rdquo;\n\nLecocq asserts that the SU's class rep training is &ldquo;primarily funded by private sponsorship&rdquo;.\n\nAs regards general cuts that will affect the students, LeCocq wishes &ldquo;to make sure the next Provost keeps to the assurances, made by the current Provost, that he will defend teaching and research in Trinity from being cut; and will not cut the arts and humanities budget in order to keep the science budget the same.&rdquo;\n\n&ldquo;I want students to be able to leave the 24 hour study room at 2am, to grab a coffee and a bite to eat, and then be able to resume their work; instead of being barred access,&rdquo; says Lecocq. &ldquo;I do not feel students should have to pay fees to use services in the Sports Centre, when they are already paying a yearly subscription.&rdquo;\n\n<em>The original version of this article incorrectly stated that Mr LeCocq had asserted that the SU is primarily funded by private sponsorship. He in fact said that the SU's Class Rep Training is funded by private sponsorship</em>", "Imageurl": "<!-- p.p1 {margin: 0.0px 0.0px 0.0px 0.0px; text-align: right; font: 13.0px 'Helvetica Neue'} p.p2 {margin: 0.0px 0.0px 0.0px 0.0px; text-align: justify; text-indent: 10.0px; font: 9.0px 'Whitney HTF'} span.s1 {letter-spacing: -0.1px} -->Sebastien LeCocq\n\nSS History &amp; Philosophy\n\n<strong>President</strong>\n\nSebastien Lecocq is an outspoken Englishman with an eye on pipping his fellow Englishman, Bartlett, to the Presidential post.\n\nAn altogether different candidate to Bartlett&rsquo;s CV-filled manifesto, Lecocq says that what he lacks in extra-curricular experience, he makes up for in dedication and ideas. The twenty-two year old has dedicated himself to getting &ldquo;the best possible grade&rdquo; in his degree and immersing himself in the Irish culture.\n\nA class rep this year, the History and Philosophy student has attended SU Council regularly to ask &ldquo;pertinent questions&rdquo;. LeCocq is of the opinion that SU is far too centred on the fees issue. While he acknowledges the importance of this issue to Trinity students, he feels that the SU is out of touch with the student body.\n\n&ldquo;For instance, though we should campaign against fees and lobby TD&rsquo;s, we should definitely not be unofficially supporting particular parties just because they support us on one issue,&rdquo; said Lecocq. &ldquo;The SU should not be affiliated with particular parties and &lsquo;suggesting&rsquo; to vote certain ways, is not part of what the SU was set up to do. After all, though a party may support us on fees does not mean that their policies, as a whole over the long-term, will be in the benefit of future students and the country as a whole.&rdquo;\n\nLecocq has a novel approach to combating the cuts in the student grant. &ldquo;I wish to introduce a grant from the SU, to these poorer students. We would not ask for this money back. I would fund this by cutting back on the costs of class rep training, and other areas of SU expenditure.&rdquo;\n\nLecocq asserts that the SU's class rep training is &ldquo;primarily funded by private sponsorship&rdquo;.\n\nAs regards general cuts that will affect the students, LeCocq wishes &ldquo;to make sure the next Provost keeps to the assurances, made by the current Provost, that he will defend teaching and research in Trinity from being cut; and will not cut the arts and humanities budget in order to keep the science budget the same.&rdquo;\n\n&ldquo;I want students to be able to leave the 24 hour study room at 2am, to grab a coffee and a bite to eat, and then be able to resume their work; instead of being barred access,&rdquo; says Lecocq. &ldquo;I do not feel students should have to pay fees to use services in the Sports Centre, when they are already paying a yearly subscription.&rdquo;\n\n<em>The original version of this article incorrectly stated that Mr LeCocq had asserted that the SU is primarily funded by private sponsorship. He in fact said that the SU's Class Rep Training is funded by private sponsorship</em>", "Thumb_nail": "http://universitytimes.ie/wp-content/uploads/2013/utlogo.jpg", "ID": "219", "Heading": "SU ELECTION CANDIDATE: Sebastian LeCocq"}